The study of scientists of the National Trust for Scotland will follow the ordinary and soprano-Lillians, as well as brown bats with long ears and daubenton bats in the Inverrow Gardens in Wester Ross.
Special cameras will be placed at key locations around the property to track the activities of bats during the season.
En-Each-Es personnel and volunteers will also carry mobile research using hand detectors.
Expert analysis of sounds from all recordings will determine the frequency depending on the bat species.
Then a map of dwellings will be developed to create a detailed picture of their behavior in the area.
Rob Dewar, a nature conservation adviser in En-Ti-Es, hopes to find out which areas of life are most important for bats and how each species uses them.
Such information will help to determine the benefits of habitat management, such as the creation of meadows and how best to maintain the forests for bats and other associated species.
The population of bats in Scotland and Britain declined significantly in the last century.
They are threatened by construction and development that affects beds and the loss of habitats.
Veterans and lights also pose risks, as well as sticky fly strips and some chemical treatments of construction materials, as well as attacks on domestic cats.
Bats aren't really blind.
Yet, because of their night hunting habits, their ears are more useful than their eyes when it comes to catching prey.
They use sophisticated echo location techniques to find insects and obstacles in the flight path.
En-Ti-Es, who cares about more than 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 hectares of land in the country, takes bats very seriously.
There are ten trained experts who regularly conduct research, inspection of beds, and sometimes rescues.
The organization even establishes the first and only bat reserve in Scotland for the Trives estate in Damfries and Galovei, home to eight of the ten species living in Scotland.
