New information on the red tide: Concentrations decline in Pinelas, Manati and Sarasota
The latest report by the Florida Committee on Fish and Wildlife shows a general decline in red tide concentrations in parts of Tampa Bay.
According to the Commission, conditions of irregular alga blooming have been observed in the area of the districts of Pinelas, Manati, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier, indicating a decrease in concentrations.
The red tide, the result of the blooming of the red algae, stretches about 130 miles off the coast of northern Pinelas County to the South Li district.
Parts of the red tide can be observed about 10 miles off the coast of Hillsborough, but the number is still smaller than last week.
Red tide has also been observed in Pascoe County.
During the past week, the following concentrations were observed: average concentrations in or on the coast of Pinelas County, low to high concentrations on the coast of Hillsborough, common to high concentrations in or on the coast of Sarasota District, common to average concentrations in Charlotte County, common to high concentrations in or on the coast of Li District, as well as low concentrations in Collier County.
In the districts of Pinelas, Manati, Sarasota, Lee and Collier, there are still cases of respiratory irritation.
No cases of respiratory irritation have been reported in Northwestern Florida during last week.
